00:48:20.760 --> 00:48:27.910
You see, when they were building the World
Trade Center it was a huge project, as you

00:48:27.910 --> 00:48:36.670
all know. And it was originally, it was originally
conceived because of money and it was also

00:48:36.670 --> 00:48:44.530
built, in a sense, that it would earn enormous
amounts of money. It was conceived because

00:48:44.530 --> 00:48:53.730
David Rockefeller, who was a big deal banker,
got the idea that he could revivify commerce

00:48:53.730 --> 00:49:01.830
in Lower Manhattan by building a trade center;
something that would simply draw in a lot

00:49:01.830 --> 00:49:11.100
of traffic. It wasn't for 20 years that they
started the competition in which the architects

00:49:11.100 --> 00:49:21.530
were chosen. Yamasaki was a good and very
successful architect. He was also Japanese-American.

00:49:21.530 --> 00:49:30.550
And to my mind, he was never fully sure of
his American identity and one of the things

00:49:30.550 --> 00:49:42.950
he did, or designed for himself in his own
mind to affirm his own identity, was to become

00:49:42.950 --> 00:49:51.060
a kind of citizen of the world; an Internationalist.
Anyway, he had his firm do at least a hundred

00:49:51.060 --> 00:49:59.150
models of the World Trade Center and they
were some pretty good stuff. He ended up with

00:49:59.150 --> 00:50:08.470
a complex that would fill the available acreage
with an 80-story skyscraper and a number of

00:50:08.470 --> 00:50:17.240
other large buildings around it. Now, if you
look south at Lower Manhattan, you'll see

00:50:17.240 --> 00:50:24.590
three or four buildings, some of them from
the early 30s, that go up 70, 60, 70, 80 stories.

00:50:24.590 --> 00:50:33.100
An 80-story skyscraper might have added very
nicely to the profile of lower New York. But

00:50:33.100 --> 00:50:38.600
the Port Authority, even though they had already
chosen Yamasaki, weren't satisfied with 80

00:50:38.600 --> 00:50:48.610
stories. What they wanted was something like
ten million square feet of office space in

00:50:48.610 --> 00:50:56.250
two buildings. And I, I don't know how many
of you remember the World Trade Center; its

00:50:56.250 --> 00:51:07.760
1350 feet tall, 110 stories. Every story in
each of those two buildings was an acre; two

00:51:07.760 --> 00:51:15.370
hundred by two hundred. That's why the buildings
looked so, in a sense, nightmarish because

00:51:15.370 --> 00:51:22.090
they were not only very tall, but they were
very, very thick. They were very wide on every

00:51:22.090 --> 00:51:31.780
side. Now, what that means is that the majority
of people, who are working on any given floor,

00:51:31.780 --> 00:51:41.020
are on average of what would it be? Seventy-five
feet, sixty feet away from the nearest window.

00:51:41.020 --> 00:51:47.360
On top of that, Yamasaki, who himself had
acrophobia, made the windows so small that

00:51:47.360 --> 00:51:52.903
you couldn't even notice the windows from
a distance. As I say in the book, "The World

00:51:52.903 --> 00:52:05.030
Trade Center, which had the world's best view,
was legally blind itself." Yamasaki did, had,

00:52:05.030 --> 00:52:13.380
what he had to do was make an uncomfortable
compromise with his clients and he created

00:52:13.380 --> 00:52:21.070
a set of buildings, which in the end, told
a lie. And here is the lie: If you look at

00:52:21.070 --> 00:52:32.390
a building like the Chrysler Building or the
old RCA building or the Liebert Building,

00:52:32.390 --> 00:52:41.650
you're looking at a concept that was humanistically
designed. It was designed to give the individual

00:52:41.650 --> 00:52:47.990
a sense that even though he was working in
a very large building, there was something

00:52:47.990 --> 00:52:54.740
about that building that justified the work.
There something beautiful, there was something

00:52:54.740 --> 00:53:05.050
human, there was something that gave vent
to the individual's aspirations. With the

00:53:05.050 --> 00:53:12.730
World Trade Center, Yamasaki was forced to
go too far. The World Trade Center was not,

00:53:12.730 --> 00:53:18.860
in a sense, justifying. It didn't justify
the individual. It belittled the individual

00:53:18.860 --> 00:53:26.500
in the same sense that it belittled the other
skyscrapers. As I put it in the book, "It

00:53:26.500 --> 00:53:36.560
stood out in the vernacular of Lower Manhattan
like a pair of hurled expletives." Expletives

00:53:36.560 --> 00:53:45.621
not deleted until the end, of course. Yamasaki's
story goes on because there were, there were

00:53:45.621 --> 00:53:57.280
other lies in the course of the development
of the building. New York code required six

00:53:57.280 --> 00:54:04.950
escape routes for buildings of that size.
The Port Authority cut them to three. The

00:54:04.950 --> 00:54:09.440
three escape routes were intertwined all the
way up to the top of the building; these were

00:54:09.440 --> 00:54:16.230
the staircases. Had there been six escape
routes, you would've probably had, now, I

00:54:16.230 --> 00:54:21.890
want each of you to become an architect, you
probably would've had one at each of the four

00:54:21.890 --> 00:54:27.110
corners of each building and then two intertwined
down the middle. That's the logical approach.

00:54:27.110 --> 00:54:33.650
If that had happened, there would've been
at least a couple of escape routes available

00:54:33.650 --> 00:54:41.590
to the people above the crash zones, when
the crash zones, crash occurred. But instead,

00:54:41.590 --> 00:54:48.740
the Port Authority limited them to three and
they were wound down the middle of the building.

00:54:48.740 --> 00:54:54.190
As it turned out, after the crashes, there
was only one open escape route, it was only

00:54:54.190 --> 00:55:05.580
partly open and only 17 people escaped down
it. Everyone else above the crash zone died.

00:55:05.580 --> 00:55:12.940
There's another lie attached to it and this
